# ERP Intelligence Platform — Engineering Rules

This is a documentation-first, AI-assisted ERP project. It follows Modular
Monolith, Clean Architecture, Domain-Driven Design and SOLID. Full context:
start from `docs/00-Overview.md`.

## Hard constraints

- Never bypass the Domain layer. Business logic belongs exclusively there.
- Never put business rules in controllers. Keep the API layer thin.
- Never couple the Domain layer to Infrastructure or any external framework.
- Use Repository Pattern / Unit of Work abstractions for persistence; never
  embed business logic in EF Core code.
- Follow the naming, API, database and Git conventions in
  `docs/database/Naming-Conventions.md`.
- Every significant implementation needs Unit Tests (and Integration Tests
  when applicable) — code without tests is incomplete.
- Update the relevant documentation in the same change as the code (docs and
  code evolve together, per `docs/04-Engineering-Handbook.md`).
- Never hardcode secrets, disable security mechanisms, or trust unvalidated
  input.

## Recurring rules (from past code reviews)

- English for all engineering artefacts — code, exception messages, logs,
  comments. Only the React frontend (end-user text) is Portuguese-first.
  Never put a Portuguese string in a domain/application exception.
- Distinguish failure kinds with typed exceptions; the controller maps them to
  HTTP status by type. Never branch on message text (`ex.Message.Contains`).
- Reuse `ERP.SharedKernel` (`Entity<TId>`, `ValueObject`, `IDomainEvent`) for
  every new domain type; `ERP.Domain` references only `ERP.SharedKernel`.
- Every new module must work end to end on a fresh database — seed the
  reference data/permissions it needs.
- Business entities are soft-deleted (deactivated), not physically deleted;
  `DELETE` endpoints return `204`.
- New frontend UI needs Vitest + React Testing Library tests; `npm test` runs
  the suite, not only `tsc`.

## Decision hierarchy

When documents conflict, resolve in this order (see
`docs/ai/Cursor-Rules.md` Section 17 for the full rationale):

1. `docs/03-Software-Architecture-Document.md`
2. `docs/04-Engineering-Handbook.md`
3. `docs/decisions/` (ADRs)
4. `docs/02-Product-Requirements-Document.md`
5. Current Sprint under `docs/backlog/`
6. `docs/backlog/Product-Backlog.md`

## Do not

- Invent business requirements or assume undocumented decisions — ask instead
  of guessing.
- Scaffold new tooling (databases, CI/CD, containers) without checking
  whether `docs/devops/DevOps-Strategy.md` or the current Sprint already
  defines how to do it.

